You can override using the `.groups` argument. career <- Master %>% tbl_df() %>% dplyr::select(playerID, nameFirst, nameLast) %>% unite(name, nameFirst, nameLast, sep = " ") %>% inner_join(career, by = "playerID") %>% dplyr::select(-playerID) ## Warning: `tbl_df()` was deprecated in dplyr 1.0.0. ## Please use `tibble::as_tibble()` instead. ## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours. ## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was generated. head(career) ## # A tibble: 6 × 5 ## name lgID H AB average ## <chr> <fct> <int> <int> <dbl> ## 1 Jeff Abbott AL 127 459 0.277 ## 2 Kurt Abbott AL 33 123 0.268 ## 3 Kurt Abbott NL 455 1780 0.256 ## 4 Reggie Abercrombie NL 54 255 0.212 ## 5 Brent Abernathy AL 194 767 0.253 ## 6 Shawn Abner AL 81 309 0.262 Question Suppose we are interested in the batting average of baseball players since 1990, that is, the average is:
\[ average = \frac{number\ of\ hits}{number\ of\ atbats} \]
Let’s first visualize this.
gf_density(~ average, data = career) %>% gf_labs(x = "Batting Average") What if we hypothesized that the batting average will differ based on the league that players played in.
gf_violin(lgID ~ average, data = career, fill = 'gray80', draw_quantiles = c('0.1', '0.5', '0.9')) %>% gf_labs(x = "Batting Average", y = "League") df_stats(average ~ lgID, data = career, mean, median, sd, IQR, min, max, length) ## response lgID mean median sd IQR min max ## 1 average AL 0.2539625 0.2567568 0.0287995 0.03696929 0.1250000 0.3488372 ## 2 average NL 0.2541274 0.2571429 0.0285979 0.03621951 0.1440678 0.3472072 ## length ## 1 1387 ## 2 1415 The distributions seem similar, but what if we wanted to go a step further and estimate a model to explore if there are really differences or not. For example, suppose we were interested in:
\[ H_{0}: \mu_{NL} = \mu_{AL} \]
\[ H_{0}: \mu_{NL} - \mu_{AL} = 0 \]
What type of model could we use? What about linear regression?
 Linear Regression with Categorical Attributes Since these notes are happening, you can assume it is possible. But how can a categorical attribute with categories rather than numbers be included in the linear regression model?
The answer is that they can’t. We need a new representation of the categorical attribute, enter dummy or indicator coding.
Dummy/Indicator Coding Suppose we use the following logic:
If NL, then give a value of 1, else give a value of 0.
Does this give the same information as before?
  League ID Dummy League ID    AL 0  NL 1    What would this look like for the actual data?
career <- career %>% mutate(league_dummy = ifelse(lgID == 'NL', 1, 0), league_dummy_al = ifelse(lgID == 'AL', 1, 0)) head(career, n = 10) ## # A tibble: 10 × 7 ## name lgID H AB average league_dummy league_dummy_al ## <chr> <fct> <int> <int> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> ## 1 Jeff Abbott AL 127 459 0.277 0 1 ## 2 Kurt Abbott AL 33 123 0.268 0 1 ## 3 Kurt Abbott NL 455 1780 0.256 1 0 ## 4 Reggie Abercrombie NL 54 255 0.212 1 0 ## 5 Brent Abernathy AL 194 767 0.253 0 1 ## 6 Shawn Abner AL 81 309 0.262 0 1 ## 7 Shawn Abner NL 19 115 0.165 1 0 ## 8 Bobby Abreu AL 858 3061 0.280 0 1 ## 9 Bobby Abreu NL 1602 5373 0.298 1 0 ## 10 Jose Abreu AL 1114 3787 0.294 0 1 Now that there is a numeric attribute, these can be added into the linear regression model.
average_lm <- lm(average ~ 1 + league_dummy, data = career) broom::tidy(average_lm) ## # A tibble: 2 × 5 ## term estimate std.error statistic p.value ## <chr> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> ## 1 (Intercept) 0.254 0.000771 330. 0 ## 2 league_dummy 0.000165 0.00108 0.152 0.879 summary(average_lm) ## ## Call: ## lm(formula = average ~ 1 + league_dummy, data = career) ## ## Residuals: ## Min 1Q Median 3Q Max ## -0.128963 -0.016770 0.002935 0.019779 0.094875 ## ## Coefficients: ## Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|) ## (Intercept) 0.2539625 0.0007706 329.578 <2e-16 *** ## league_dummy 0.0001649 0.0010843 0.152 0.879 ## --- ## Signif. codes: 0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1 ## ## Residual standard error: 0.0287 on 2800 degrees of freedom ## Multiple R-squared: 8.257e-06, Adjusted R-squared: -0.0003489 ## F-statistic: 0.02312 on 1 and 2800 DF, p-value: 0.8792 head(model.matrix(average_lm)) ## (Intercept) league_dummy ## 1 1 0 ## 2 1 0 ## 3 1 1 ## 4 1 1 ## 5 1 0 ## 6 1 0 How are these terms interpreted now?
df_stats(average ~ league_dummy, data = career, mean, sd, length) ## response league_dummy mean sd length ## 1 average 0 0.2539625 0.0287995 1387 ## 2 average 1 0.2541274 0.0285979 1415  Switch reference group average_lm_al <- lm(average ~ league_dummy_al, data = career) summary(average_lm_al) ## ## Call: ## lm(formula = average ~ league_dummy_al, data = career) ## ## Residuals: ## Min 1Q Median 3Q Max ## -0.128963 -0.016770 0.002935 0.019779 0.094875 ## ## Coefficients: ## Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|) ## (Intercept) 0.2541274 0.0007629 333.104 <2e-16 *** ## league_dummy_al -0.0001649 0.0010843 -0.152 0.879 ## --- ## Signif. codes: 0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1 ## ## Residual standard error: 0.0287 on 2800 degrees of freedom ## Multiple R-squared: 8.257e-06, Adjusted R-squared: -0.0003489 ## F-statistic: 0.02312 on 1 and 2800 DF, p-value: 0.8792 \[ H_{A}: \mu_{NL} - \mu_{AL} > 0 \]
\[ H_{A}: \mu_{NL} > \mu_{AL} \]
head(career) ## # A tibble: 6 × 7 ## name lgID H AB average league_dummy league_dummy_al ## <chr> <fct> <int> <int> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> ## 1 Jeff Abbott AL 127 459 0.277 0 1 ## 2 Kurt Abbott AL 33 123 0.268 0 1 ## 3 Kurt Abbott NL 455 1780 0.256 1 0 ## 4 Reggie Abercrombie NL 54 255 0.212 1 0 ## 5 Brent Abernathy AL 194 767 0.253 0 1 ## 6 Shawn Abner AL 81 309 0.262 0 1 average_lm2 <- lm(average ~ lgID, data = career) broom::tidy(average_lm2) ## # A tibble: 2 × 5 ## term estimate std.error statistic p.value ## <chr> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> ## 1 (Intercept) 0.254 0.000771 330. 0 ## 2 lgIDNL 0.000165 0.00108 0.152 0.879  Show equivalent t-tests t.test(average ~ lgID, data = career, var.equal = TRUE) ## ## Two Sample t-test ## ## data: average by lgID ## t = -0.15205, df = 2800, p-value = 0.8792 ## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group AL and group NL is not equal to 0 ## 95 percent confidence interval: ## -0.002291074 0.001961316 ## sample estimates: ## mean in group AL mean in group NL ## 0.2539625 0.2541274 t.test(average ~ lgID, data = career) ## ## Welch Two Sample t-test ## ## data: average by lgID ## t = -0.15204, df = 2798, p-value = 0.8792 ## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group AL and group NL is not equal to 0 ## 95 percent confidence interval: ## -0.002291224 0.001961466 ## sample estimates: ## mean in group AL mean in group NL ## 0.2539625 0.2541274  Test for equal variances library(car) ## Loading required package: carData ## ## Attaching package: 'carData' ## The following object is masked from 'package:Lahman': ## ## Salaries ## ## Attaching package: 'car' ## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr': ## ## recode ## The following object is masked from 'package:purrr': ## ## some leveneTest(average ~ lgID, data = career) ## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median) ## Df F value Pr(>F) ## group 1 0.1735 0.6771 ## 2800
title: Regression Categorical Predictors

content:
The following activity is aimed to give you some practice with exploring data and running a linear regression on your own using statistical software. You are welcome to use any statistical software you wish and you are also free to work in groups of up to 3 for this assignment. If you work in groups, please submit one completed activity per group on ICON. Please make sure to add everyone’s name to the submission, this can be a comment on ICON or on the document itself.
What to turn in? Please turn in a document that contains answers to the following questions and also please include any relevant statistics/figures that support your answer. Upload the final document to ICON.
Due around September 26th, 2021. No penalty for late submissions as long as it is submitted by December 12th.
Data The data for this activity is rideshare data from about three weeks in 2018 for Boston, MA. The data originally come from Kaggle. I have done some processing to randomly select 2,500 records from the larger data for our use and have trimmed down the data attributes.
The data can be obtained in csv format. A short description for each attribute is as follows.
   Attribute Name Description     id Unique identifier for each row   hour The hour of the ride   day The day of the ride   month The month of the ride, either 11 = November or 12 = December   price The total price of the ride, in $   temperature The outside temperature at the time of the ride, in Fahrenheit   distance Total distance of the ride, in miles   surge_multiplier The surge multiplier for the cost of rides   humidity The humidity at the time of the ride    Guiding Question Does the distance of the ride explain variation in the price of the ride?
Questions   Explore the distribution of the price of the rides descriptively. In a few sentences, summarize key elements of the distribution, for instance discussing elements related to shape, center, variation, and/or extreme values.
  Explore the bivariate distribution of the price of ride and distance of rides. In a few sentences, summarize key elements of the relationship between price and distance. You may wish to include the following elements of the association, strength, direction, and/or form.
  Does the association between price and distance of rides appear to be linear? Why or why not?
  Fit a linear regression to answer the research question highlighted above. Interpret the intercept and slope of the linear regression. That is, what do these terms mean?
  What are the r-squared and sigma estimates from the linear regression? Interpret these two values in the context of the problem. That is, what do these two terms mean in the context of the data and this problem?
  Finally, in a couple sentences, provide a summary of the overall model. Does the model appear to be useful to predict the price of a ride with only the distance of the ride? Use statistics from the analysis steps above to support your answer.
summary: The following activity is aimed to give you some practice with exploring data and running a linear regression on your own using statistical software. You are welcome to use any statistical software you wish and you are also free to work in groups of up to 3 for this assignment.
title: Activity 1

content:
The following activity is aimed to give you some practice with exploring data and running a linear regression on your own using statistical software. You are welcome to use any statistical software you wish and you are also free to work in groups of up to 3 for this assignment. If you work in groups, please submit one completed activity per group on ICON. Please make sure to add everyone’s name to the submission, this can be a comment on ICON or on the document itself.
What to turn in? Please turn in a document that contains answers to the following questions and also please include any relevant statistics/figures that support your answer. Upload the final document to ICON.
Due around October 10th, 2021. No penalty for late submissions as long as it is submitted by December 12th.
Data The data for this activity is rideshare data from about three weeks in 2018 for Boston, MA. The data originally come from Kaggle. I have done some processing to randomly select 2,500 records from the larger data for our use and have trimmed down the data attributes.
Note: Use the data linked here or posted to the IDAS. The data can be obtained in csv format. A short description for each attribute is as follows.
   Attribute Name Description     id Unique identifier for each row   hour The hour of the ride   day The day of the ride   month The month of the ride, either 11 = November or 12 = December   price The total price of the ride, in $   temperature The outside temperature at the time of the ride, in Fahrenheit   distance Total distance of the ride, in miles   surge_multiplier The surge multiplier for the cost of rides   humidity The humidity at the time of the ride    Guiding Question Does the distance of the ride explain variation in the price of the ride?
Questions   This assignment uses the same data from the first activity. Take a few minutes to reacquaint yourself with this analysis, including the linear regression estimates obtained.
  Was the intercept from the linear regression fitted in activity 1 using the raw data as is interpretable in the context of the data? Rephrasing slightly, could the intercept term be made more interpretable? If so, how?
  Fit a modified linear regression that performs a centering. That is, center the distance in some fashion. Options could include, minimum, mean, median, maximum, etc centering. What changed for the estimates obtained from the model?
 Which model, the centered or the uncentered, do you feel has a stronger justification for its usage? Be as specific as possible in your rationale.    Use whichever model you feel is the best from #3, then extract from software or compute the standard errors for the estimated regression coefficients. Interpret these standard errors in the context of the problem.
  Compute confidence intervals for the two regression coefficients. Justify your choice for level of confidence and interpret the confidence interval.
  Finally, perform hypothesis testing for the two regression coefficients. In this, set up the null/alternative hypotheses and then interpret the statistical results to provide a statistical conclusion. More specifically, what does the hypothesis test suggest about the null and alternative hypotheses?
 The first part talked about the statistical conclusions, now compare/contrast this with practical conclusions. More specifically, would these results be useful in practice? Be as specific as possible in your response.

title: Activity 2

content:
The following activity is aimed to give you some practice with exploring data and running a linear regression on your own using statistical software. You are welcome to use any statistical software you wish and you are also free to work in groups of up to 3 for this assignment. If you work in groups, please submit one completed activity per group on ICON. Please make sure to add everyone’s name to the submission, this can be a comment on ICON or on the document itself.
What to turn in? Please turn in a document that contains answers to the following questions and also please include any relevant statistics/figures that support your answer. Upload the final document to ICON.
Due around November 30th, 2021. No penalty for late submissions as long as it is submitted by December 12th.
Data The data for this activity is pumpkin data from 2021 for those growing giant pumpkins, original data from Big Pumpkins.
Note: Use the data linked here or posted to the IDAS. The data can be obtained in csv format. A short description for each attribute is as follows.
   Attribute Name Description     place Place of pumpkin based on weight (ie, rank)   weight_lbs Pumpkin weight, in lbs   name Name of grower   city City of grower   state_prov State or Province of grower   country Country of grower   gpc_site Site pumpkin was weighed   seed_mother Seed of pumpkin   pollinator_father Pumpkin pollinator   ott Over the top of the pumpkin measurement, in inches   est_weight Estimated weight, in lbs   pct_chart The percent on chart   us_dummy A dummy/indicator attribute, 1 = United States grower, 0 = otherwise   us_region A categorical attribute, west, south, northeast, midwest, other (other is outside United States locations). Regions were coded based on Census Bureau designated regions (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_regions_of_the_United_States)    Guiding Question  How much variation is explained in the pumpkin weight (weight_lbs) by the over the top pumpkin measurement? a. After controlling for pumpkin over the top measurement, is there any differences between United States growers compared to growers from other countries?  Questions   Explore the research questions descriptively. What are key messages based on the descriptive analysis?
  Fit a linear regression model to explore the first research question. Summarize the key messages/takeaways from the results of this regression model.
  Fit a second linear regression model to explore the subquestion above. Summarize the key messages/takeaways from the results of this regression model.
  Fit the third linear regression model that includes an interaction between the two primary attributes of interest from the research questions.
  Finally, instead of comparing United States vs other countries, try a new series of models equivalent to #3 and #4 that break the United States by their region (ie, use us_region). a. Are all of these models nested? b. Perform the appropriate model comparison to identify the best fitting model.
  Is the added complexity of splitting the United States into specific regions justified? Why or why not?
summary: The following activity is aimed to give you some practice with exploring data and running a linear regression on your own using statistical software. You are welcome to use any statistical software you wish and you are also free to work in groups of up to 3 for this assignment.
